Class BaseLSRLEfficiencyCalibrator

All Implemented Interfaces:

Direct Known Subclasses:
LSRLEfficiencyCalibrator
public abstract class BaseLSRLEfficiencyCalibrator
extends AbstractRegressionEfficiencyCalibrator

Not intended to be used directly, but rather overridden by other classes using a LSRL as their mathematical base. In these overriding classes, you will most likely want to override translateCmps and inverseTranslateCmps.

Unlike LSRLEfficiencyCalibrator, this class does not publicly expose the slope and intercept information.

getRValue

public double getRValue()
Gets the Pearson product-moment correlation coefficient, or "r" value. The value is from -1 to 1. A high magnitude (close to -1 or 1) means a strong correlation. A value close to zero means a weak correlation. You want a high r-value.

Returns:
The r-value if it is defined for this LSRL, otherwise NaN.

translateCmps

public double translateCmps(double oldCmps)
Description copied from interface: IEfficiencyCalibrator
Divides the desired cmps by the efficiency at that cmps. In other words, it returns the speed that the motor should be told to move at in order to actually get it to move at the desired speed.

inverseTranslateCmps

public double inverseTranslateCmps(double cmps)
Description copied from interface: IRegressionEfficiencyCalibrator
Performs the reverse of what translateCmps does. In other words, neglecting rounding errors,
inverseTranslateCmps(translateCmps(x)) == x
